00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:24.480
PROFESSOR: So last time we were
starting more complicated

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:37.760
mechanisms and we looked
at series reactions.

00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:40.220
A goes B, which is
an intermediate.

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:43.830
Goes to C with rates
k1 and k2.

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:49.380
And we solved the
problem exactly.

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:52.470
Which turned out to be a
little bit complicated.

00:00:52.470 --> 00:00:58.030
And then we were looking
at special cases.

00:00:58.030 --> 00:01:05.350
And I left the special case
of k1 equals k2 to do as a

00:01:05.350 --> 00:01:08.510
homework problem.

00:01:08.510 --> 00:01:14.390
And then on the board we did
k1 much greater than k2.

00:01:14.390 --> 00:01:22.680
Which looks like, if k1 is much
greater than k2, the rate

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:27.660
into k1 is much greater than
k2, so using the analogy of

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:35.860
buckets and pipes, it's a big
pipe between k1 and between A

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:39.090
and B. And a little pipe
between B and C and you

00:01:39.090 --> 00:01:41.250
started with a bunch
of liquid on top.

00:01:41.250 --> 00:01:45.270
And you basically dump
it into here.

00:01:45.270 --> 00:01:49.380
And then you slowly
drip into C here.

00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:54.160
So the first thing that happens
is that A gets dumped,

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:56.840
it becomes B very quickly.

00:01:56.840 --> 00:01:58.840
With a rate constant k1.

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:02.260
In a first order fashion.

00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:07.460
So A is A0 e to the minus
k1 times time.

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:10.710
Then B comes up sharply.

00:02:10.710 --> 00:02:18.610
And then drops down with rate
constant k2 slowly.

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:24.750
So B is approximately A0 e to
the minus k2 times time.

00:02:24.750 --> 00:02:30.240
And then C has a very small
quadratic rise, followed by

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:33.790
the exponential rise to
saturation that you'd expect.

00:02:33.790 --> 00:02:39.300
So C is approximately a0 times
one minus e to the minus k2

00:02:39.300 --> 00:02:40.080
times time.

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:43.300
The rate constant k2 dominates
the long times.

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:45.890
And everything it's looking like
it's pseudo first order

00:02:45.890 --> 00:02:47.310
at long times.

00:02:47.310 --> 00:02:51.680
So you can do this either by
thinking about it, solve the

00:02:51.680 --> 00:02:55.650
problem by thinking about it,
which is perfectly fine.

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:58.250
Or you can do it by solving
it exactly, as we

00:02:58.250 --> 00:03:00.060
have done last time.

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:02.500
And then putting in the
right approximations.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:06.320
Which in this case was Taylor's
approximation, if I

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:08.900
remember right.

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:12.110
And know just by looking at the
equation and putting the

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:14.100
right approximation,
you get it out.

00:03:14.100 --> 00:03:22.030
And a third approximation, which
is the opposite one, k2

00:03:22.030 --> 00:03:28.260
much less than k1, so k1 much
less than k2, the way that

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:39.720
that's going to look, we can
do it by inspection.

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:43.970
So basically if we think of
buckets and pipes, that's a

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:48.440
very thin pipe connecting the
bucket for A and B, so we drip

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:52.560
from A to B, then we have this
very fat pipe connecting B and

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:56.710
C. So as soon as a little B gets
in there, it immediately

00:03:56.710 --> 00:04:01.740
becomes C. So, the rate
determining step is the first

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:06.620
one, A goes to B. And so k1, we
expect that to be the rate

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:09.770
that dominates the long time.

00:04:09.770 --> 00:04:17.230
And we never expect to get any
significant amount of B to

00:04:17.230 --> 00:04:19.620
pile up in the middle bucket,
because this pipe is much

00:04:19.620 --> 00:04:22.180
bigger than that one here.

00:04:22.180 --> 00:04:28.860
Therefore, what we expect to see
is a slow decay in A, with

00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:32.730
rate constant k1 dominating
the long times, A is

00:04:32.730 --> 00:04:40.070
approximately A0 e to the
minus k1 times the time.

00:04:40.070 --> 00:04:46.910
We don't expect B to amount
to very much at all.

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:49.220
It'll rise up a little bit at
the very early times, and

00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:52.210
it'll pretty much stay
very, very small.

00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:53.700
Not quite constant.

00:04:53.700 --> 00:05:01.450
And in fact if you look at the
full result, and you put in

00:05:01.450 --> 00:05:05.680
your approximations, and I'll
let you do that, you would

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:10.675
find that B is essentially
related to A through a

00:05:10.675 --> 00:05:15.500
constant term where k1 is very
small compared to k2.

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:17.530
So this is a very small
number here.

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:20.120
B is equal to a very small
number times A. So it

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:24.670
basically follows A, but at
a very very, low level.

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:33.850
And then you would find that C
rises up in approximately e to

00:05:33.850 --> 00:05:37.990
the minus k1 times t, so
with rate constant k1.

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:45.700
One minus e to the minus
k1 times the time.

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:49.370
So the dominant rate is k1, and
in this case here this is

00:05:49.370 --> 00:05:52.250
an approximation that we're
going to see again.

00:05:52.250 --> 00:05:56.120
We're going to revisit this
approximation here when we get

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:57.870
to more complicated mechanisms,
it's going to

00:05:57.870 --> 00:06:01.340
become this steady state
approximation.

00:06:01.340 --> 00:06:03.710
Where the amount of the
intermediate, or the

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:07.250
concentration of intermediate,
is low at all times.

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:09.150
And doesn't change very fast.

00:06:09.150 --> 00:06:11.220
The slope here is very slow.

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:14.980
Because k1 is so slow coming
down, and B is related to A,

00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:19.850
which means it's related to this
slow decrease in A, the

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:22.350
amount of B is small and the
rate of change in B is also

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:24.070
very small.

00:06:24.070 --> 00:06:25.610
And hopefully we'll
get to that very

00:06:25.610 --> 00:06:28.530
soon in this lecture.

00:06:28.530 --> 00:06:31.900
OK, so that's a summary of
what we did last time.

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:36.540
Any questions?

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:50.050
So the next thing now is to
go to the next mechanism.

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:51.960
Which is, so far we've looked
at reactions that

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:53.910
proceed all the way.

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:55.200
We haven't looked at
equilibrium yet.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:58.120
But we know thermodynamics
is all about equilibrium.

00:06:58.120 --> 00:07:01.970
So now we're going to connect
kinetics and thermodynamics.

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:05.620
We're going to look at a
mechanism which is an

00:07:05.620 --> 00:07:09.400
equilibrium mechanism.

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:16.920
Equilibrium or reversible
reactions.

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:21.380
Where you have A goes to B, with
summary constant k1, but

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:24.600
you can have the reverse process
B goes back to A with

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:27.870
the rate constant k minus one.

00:07:27.870 --> 00:07:35.240
Or you can write is as A k1, k
minus one to B, where k1 could

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:39.600
be k forward and k minus one
could be k backwards.

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:42.330
Also written as k sub
f, and this is also

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:46.110
written as k sub b.

00:07:46.110 --> 00:07:47.290
So now we have more

00:07:47.290 --> 00:07:49.360
information than we had before.

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:51.930
Because now we know this is
an equilibrium problem.

00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:54.830
And we already know about
equilibrium from

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:55.020
thermodynamics.

00:07:55.020 --> 00:08:00.840
And we know that at equilibrium,
in addition to

00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:03.580
all the rate laws that we're
going to write down to solve

00:08:03.580 --> 00:08:06.940
the problem, we also know
that at equilibrium, the

00:08:06.940 --> 00:08:09.900
equilibrium constant is related
to the equilibrium

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:11.980
concentrations.

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:14.130
To the ratio of the equilibrium
concentrations.

00:08:14.130 --> 00:08:19.040
This is something additional
that we have.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:20.900
So let's write down everything
we know.

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:24.290
And our goal is to find
out the time, the

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:25.420
dynamics of this problem.

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:28.400
Suppose you start at some time
t equals zero, at a certain

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:32.030
amount of A0 in your pot, a
certain amount of B0, how do

00:08:32.030 --> 00:08:33.270
you get to equilibrium.

00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:37.240
What's the rate, what
does it look like?

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:41.790
So the first thing is to
write down the rates.

00:08:41.790 --> 00:08:47.300
So the forward rate minus dA/dt,
which is the forward

00:08:47.300 --> 00:08:53.000
rate, R sub forward is equal
to k1 times A. And the

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:58.200
backwards rate, minus dB/dt,
which we can write as R sub

00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:15.750
backwards, that's k minus one
times B. At equilibrium, we

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:16.790
have no dynamics.

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:19.450
Or no ensemble dynamics.

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:21.610
The pot looks constant.

00:09:21.610 --> 00:09:24.330
It doesn't look like anything's
going on in there.

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:26.300
The concentration of
A doesn't change.

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:27.930
The concentration of
B doesn't change.

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:32.510
They're constant at the
equilibrium concentration.

00:09:32.510 --> 00:09:36.600
So that implies that the rate
of formation of B must be

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:39.620
equal to the rate of destruction
of B. Or, in other

00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:44.890
words, that the rate forward at
equilibrium has to be equal

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:46.280
the rate backwards.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:50.020
Otherwise, there'd be changes
in concentrations.

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:54.930
So if that's true, then that
means that at equilibrium, k1

00:09:54.930 --> 00:10:02.050
A equilibrium has to be equal to
k minus one B equilibrium.

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:10.990
Which means that we can get this
ratio of B to A. And see

00:10:10.990 --> 00:10:16.830
that this is equal to
k1 over k minus one.

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:19.970
So we've just, this is
pretty major here.

00:10:19.970 --> 00:10:22.170
Looks pretty simple,
but we've taken an

00:10:22.170 --> 00:10:24.350
equilibrium property here.

00:10:24.350 --> 00:10:27.900
And related to kinetics.

00:10:27.900 --> 00:10:34.440
To a rate property.

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:37.070
So here we have kinetics.

00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:46.440
Here we have thermo.

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:49.960
And this is going to turn out
to be, this kind of ratio

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:52.530
between forward rates and
backwards rates, related to

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:55.180
equilibrium constants is going
to be valid, not just for this

00:10:55.180 --> 00:10:58.730
very simple mechanism we have
here with just two species.

00:10:58.730 --> 00:11:01.270
But it's going to be valid
for more complicated.

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:03.510
And we have two species reacting
to form another

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:09.050
species, or bimolecular
stuff, et cetera.

00:11:09.050 --> 00:11:11.460
OK, so now we've laid
the groundwork,

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:12.990
let's look at the dynamics.

00:11:12.990 --> 00:11:14.820
Let's look at the
time evolution.

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:19.210
So that means that we need
to take, well this

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:19.980
is not quite right.

00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:22.230
I shouldn't write minus dA/dt.

00:11:22.230 --> 00:11:32.380
This is minus dA/dt rate forward
in the absence of

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:38.290
reverse process.

00:11:38.290 --> 00:11:41.550
It says just the destruction of
A and not the creation of

00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:48.550
A. So if you look at the full
kinetics, the full mechanism,

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:51.560
this also, the rate backwards is
minus dB/dt, in the absence

00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:55.360
of forming B back through
the reverse process.

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:58.590
So both of these are
in the absence of

00:11:58.590 --> 00:11:59.700
their reverse process.

00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:07.150
The full kinetics, for the
destruction of A. A is the

00:12:07.150 --> 00:12:11.470
rate backwards, or the rate
forwards, which is k1 times A,

00:12:11.470 --> 00:12:14.030
and then the rate backwards,
which is the creation of A.

00:12:14.030 --> 00:12:15.840
That's the two rates together.

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:19.860
Minus k minus one times B.
There's the formation of A

00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:23.050
here, this is the destruction
of A. This is the full

00:12:23.050 --> 00:12:24.960
differential equation for
the full mechanism.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:26.760
Not just one part of it.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:28.990
This one here is just for the
first step, and that one here

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:31.090
is for the second step.

00:12:31.090 --> 00:12:34.920
This is what we need to solve.

00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:40.690
But now we have a lot of help
by what we've already done.

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:44.320
So, what we can do is well, the
problem here is that's it

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:47.080
looks hard because there's
B included in here.

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:48.970
This is not just A,
there's B in here.

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:50.380
But there's only two species.

00:12:50.380 --> 00:12:52.580
And stoichiometry is going
to help us out.

00:12:52.580 --> 00:12:55.500
Remember last time, or a few
times ago, we said the last

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:57.990
species is the easy one.

00:12:57.990 --> 00:13:00.340
Because it's always related to
the concentration of all the

00:13:00.340 --> 00:13:02.790
other species by
stoichiometry.

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:06.400
And the last one here is B. So
we know that B is related to

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:11.130
A. B is whatever you
started out with.

00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:15.450
Plus whatever you used
up for A. That's one

00:13:15.450 --> 00:13:17.040
way of writing it.

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:23.310
So you start with this amount,
and you create this amount.

00:13:23.310 --> 00:13:24.950
By having A react.

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:27.480
This is what you started with,
A, and this is what's left.

00:13:27.480 --> 00:13:31.560
The difference has to go into
B. So stroke stoichiometry

00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:38.480
give you a relationship, which
you can use to plug into your

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:41.230
differential equation here.

00:13:41.230 --> 00:13:43.740
And now, after rearranging your
differential equation,

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:49.150
putting B in there, you can
rewrite this as k1 plus k

00:13:49.150 --> 00:14:01.310
minus one times A minus k minus
one times B0 plus A0.

00:14:01.310 --> 00:14:03.380
Something which depends
on A, something

00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:07.900
which is constant here.

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:08.770
OK, and what else do we know?

00:14:08.770 --> 00:14:10.180
We know something about
equilibrium.

00:14:10.180 --> 00:14:14.000
We know something about when
we reach a state where the

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.830
rate forward is equal to
the rate backward.

00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:21.510
When the rate forward is equal
to the rate backwards, the

00:14:21.510 --> 00:14:24.760
rate of change of A is zero.

00:14:24.760 --> 00:14:25.590
A is not changing.

00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:27.070
The concentration of
A is not changing.

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:38.170
So at equilibrium, dA/dt
is equal to zero.

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:42.850
And just like in this example
here, this is going to turn

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:44.980
out to be related to an
approximation called the

00:14:44.980 --> 00:14:48.170
steady state approximation,
which we're going to see later

00:14:48.170 --> 00:14:51.560
this morning.

00:14:51.560 --> 00:14:55.070
Writing at equilibrium that
the change in the

00:14:55.070 --> 00:14:57.770
concentration of one of the
species is equal to zero,

00:14:57.770 --> 00:15:00.320
we're going to use that as an
approximation also later, when

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:02.570
we get to more complicated
mechanisms.

00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:04.830
This is going to be the
equilibrium approximation.

00:15:04.830 --> 00:15:08.740
And this is going to be the
steady state approximation.

00:15:08.740 --> 00:15:12.500
Let's keep going with our, we're
solving this guy here.

00:15:12.500 --> 00:15:14.660
So at equilibrium, dA/dt
is equal to zero.

00:15:14.660 --> 00:15:27.280
And then we can replace our
concentrations here with, and

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:30.890
so if you write equal to zero
here, then we can write it as

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:32.040
equilibrium right here.

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:35.250
And we'll be able to solve for
A equilibrium in terms of k1,

00:15:35.250 --> 00:15:40.580
k minus one, B0, and A0.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:44.250
And then if you do that, you get
A equilibrium is equal to

00:15:44.250 --> 00:15:53.000
k minus one over k1 plus k minus
one times B0 plus A0.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:16:00.870
And we're going to need that.

00:16:00.870 --> 00:16:05.700
Because now we're going to be
able to plug this, so there's

00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:07.540
A0 plus B0 sitting here.

00:16:07.540 --> 00:16:10.880
And we're going to replace
A0 plus B0 in terms of A

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:12.030
equilibrium.

00:16:12.030 --> 00:16:15.320
There's a minus sign here.

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:21.730
And between this A and this
A equilibrium here, so by

00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:27.060
rewriting, by plugging in A B0
A equilibrium instead of B0

00:16:27.060 --> 00:16:36.830
plus A0, we can rewrite that
equation as dA/dt is equal to

00:16:36.830 --> 00:16:45.310
k1 plus k minus one times
A minus A equilibrium.

00:16:45.310 --> 00:16:48.020
This is nice because, this
quantity, A minus A

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:52.890
equilibrium, describes the
difference between where are

00:16:52.890 --> 00:16:55.070
you are and where
you want to be.

00:16:55.070 --> 00:16:56.820
It's a nice variable to have.

00:16:56.820 --> 00:16:59.960
It's going to change in time and
at infinite time, this is

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:01.560
going to go to zero.

00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:03.510
A is going to go
to equilibrium.

00:17:03.510 --> 00:17:05.500
A equilibrium is a constant.

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:08.110
Now we have a differential
equation that relates A to

00:17:08.110 --> 00:17:10.440
this difference.

00:17:10.440 --> 00:17:12.500
But A equilibrium
is a constant.

